I've just spent far too long trying to deploy a project to heroku and its all the sidekiq and the redis' fault!! If you really want you can go view the project here.

I had the problem where I tried to set up a sidekiq worker on heroku but these even though they said they were free wouldn't allow me to use the redis add ons without giving them credit card details and I didn't want it to run over without me knowing.The solution was to use puma to to run the server, I initially tried unicorn but from what I saw it looks like its fallen into disrepair and puma was heroku's preference also. Puma allows me to run the workers essentially without heroku knowing, as they are ran on the same dyno as heroku calls them. wouldn't allow me to use the redis add ons without giving them credit card details and I didn't want it to run over without

flowRoot.flowPara: me knowing.The solution was to use puma to to run the server, I initially tried unicorn but from what I saw it looks like its fallen into disrepair and puma was heroku's preference also. Puma allows me to run the workers essentially without
heroku knowing, as they are ran on the same dyno as heroku calls them. This is a cost saving method but it would
probably decrease performance of the site especially on a larger website with more active workers.
